<TITLE> Journalists protest Amar Desh closure </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, June 2 (bdnews24.com) Journalists and other professionals held a protest meeting and took out a procession on Wednesday demanding reopening of Bengali-language daily newspaper Amar Desh. They also demanded release of the newspaper's acting editor Mahmudur Rahman, threatening to take out more serious protests if he was not released by Saturday Chaired by Ruhul Amin Gazi, the president of one faction of the Bangladesh Federation Union of Journalists, the meeting was addressed by former advisory editor Ataus Samad, opposition chief whip Zainal Abedin Farroque, BNP MP Abul Khair Bhuiyan, Jamaat-e-Islami MP Hamidur Rahman Azad, Dr Jahid Hossain, former president of Doctors' Association of Bangladesh, Kamrul Hasan, a leader of the Professionals Forum, poet Abdul Hai Shikder and the filmmaker Chasi Nazrul Islam. The speakers said whilst the government talks about democracy, it has already closed down two television channels and are now conspiring to close down national newspapers. As a part of this conspiracy, they speakers claimed, the Amar Desh editor was picked up. They said the government had now created serious problems for itself and will in the long run suffer for these decisions. Following the meeting, the journalists and professionals took out a protest rally that started from Topkhana and ended at National Press Club. Police early on Wednesday morning stormed the Amar Desh newspaper office and arrested acting editor Mahmudur Rahman on fraud charges, hours after the government closed the BNP-leaning daily, the evening before Further protest rallies and processions have been scheduled for Thursday and Saturday morning. bdnew
